column1: How many countries will Russia remove from its food embargo list before 6 August 2016?
column5: ['0', 'Between 1 and 5, inclusive', 'More than five, but less than all', 'All']
column6: ['Economic Policy', 'Foreign Policy']
column11: This question has been closed under answer option "a)0" with an end date of 5 August 2016. Russia extended its food embargo through the end of 2017 (RT, Sputnik International). While there have been modifications to the embargo, notably to allow the importation of certain products for use in baby food (Russia Beyond the Headlines, Tass), all of the embargoed countries remain on the list. Russia imposed an embargo on food imports from the US, EU member states, Canada, Australia, and Norway in August 2014 as retaliation for western sanctions, later adding Iceland, Albania, Montenegro, and Liechtenstein to the list (Yahoo News). On 16 September 2015, Russia lifted the embargo on specialized products for sports nutrition (LatestNewsResource), but most of the embargo remains in place for all affected countries. If new countries are added to the list before the question expires, their subsequent removal will count. This question will be scored using the ordered categorial scoring rule. For more information, see the FAQ. Recommended Questions Will President Putin meet with Prime Minister Abe in Japan before 1 July 2016? Will any NATO member invoke Article 4 in response to actions taken by Russia before 1 January 2017? Will Vladimir Putin attend the Nuclear Security Summit in Washington, DC, in March 2016?

Plus, oil prices are still at rock bottom and I'm sure that Russia would like to see some foreign currency coming in from ag. exports. So yeah, could be time for a spring thaw.

The low global prices for soft commodities are amplified within Europe with lower demand from Russia because of sanctions. EU farmers care more about their farms and family's well being than anything in Ukraine, hence the current protests in France. Russian people are paying almost twice as much for some food products compared to before sanctions. With upcoming elections United Russia and Putin have a lot of incentive to lift food embargoes as a first step in relief to Russian's daily lives. Eastern European farmers at some point will begin to wonder about their allegiance to an EU whose policies force them to accept unwanted refugees and not to sell their products to their traditional key market, Russia. Farmers' lives and incomes are measured in crop years, not calendar years. If the sanctions are not lifted before summer planting or at least before fall harvest, then they have already lost another year. If sanctions are lifted this year, it should happen before August to satisfy that need. http://www.france24.com/en/20160215-france-angry-farmers-blockade-vannes-protest-falling-prices

Lately, Russia has been adding countries to its food embargo list: Iceland, Liechtenstein, Albania and Montenegro, with the prospect of adding Ukraine in 2016 if it signs an agreement with the EU. (http://www.bbc.com/news/world-33905340 ) It will try to increase imports from countries that it finds less objectionable. Meanwhile, the disgruntlement of Russian consumers will be held in check by the traditional remedy for economic bans: smuggling. Belarus is now shipping genuine Parmigiano-Reggiano cheese, made only in a few regions in Italy, into Russia with "Made in Belarus" labels slapped over the top of the original Italian labels, for instance. Smuggling will continue apace, because it is lucrative for the smugglers, desirable for the consumers, and a nice income source for suborned customs officials. Russia cannot stop it all; look at cigarettes that come across the US border from Canada for a prime example of the failure of that economic remedy.

There are several ways I could see this question resolving: 0: This is the status quo, where Russia keeps the embargo going until its scheduled expiry date (at least). This seems very unlikely; if Russia is lifting the embargo on most countries, it would be weird to still keep some on the embargo list. All: Russia lifts the embargo completely. This is quite possible if Russia and the West reach some sort of accommodation in the next year. I think this is the second most likely option.
